+**Lifecycle premise (load-bearing — read before §2).** The
+single-experiment orchestrator is **not unconditionally long-running**:
+it exits cleanly when the experiment goes quiescent
+([`loop.py`](../../reference/services/orchestrator/src/eden_orchestrator/loop.py)
+§146, after `max_quiescent_iterations` no-progress iterations), and the
+Compose deployment intentionally does **not** restart a clean exit
+([`compose.yaml`](../../reference/compose/compose.yaml) `restart:
+on-failure`). Therefore the precise behavior this chunk delivers is:
+**cadence checkpoints happen while the orchestrator is active, and a
+terminal checkpoint happens if the orchestrator observes the experiment
+terminate before it exits.** This is the right fit for the AWS-MVP
+posture — the window we care about is the *active* experiment (workers
+producing, the operator at risk of a terminate-by-mistake). A
+quiescent-but-not-terminated experiment whose orchestrator has already
+exited is not being checkpointed; for that the operator either keeps the
+orchestrator alive (a high `max_quiescent_iterations`, which the
+manual-UI playbook already recommends) or uses the manual
+`eden-experiment checkpoint`. Continuous checkpointing of an idle
+experiment with no live orchestrator is what the deferred sibling-container
+checkpointer (§4.2) would add; it is explicitly not v0. This premise is
+stated plainly here so the cadence guarantee is never over-read.
+
