-once on the loop's exit paths. **Known gap:** if the orchestrator has
-already exited (quiescence) before an admin later terminates, no
-terminal checkpoint fires — the most recent periodic checkpoint is the
-safety net. A server-side on-terminate hook would close this but needs
-the task-store-server to own a destination + repo bundle + admin
-context; deferred to a follow-up (§4.2).
+### D6 — On-terminate is gated on an *observed* `terminated` state
 
+The terminal checkpoint fires **only** when the loop observes
+`read_experiment_state() == "terminated"` (the loop drains
+post-terminate, so it has iterations to observe it — whether the
+transition came from its own `termination_policy` or an admin). It is
+**never** fired on a plain quiescent-but-running exit; otherwise a normal
+healthy quiescence would drop a misleading `-terminated-` archive. A
+final terminal re-check runs once on the loop's exit paths, also gated on
+an observed `terminated` state (covers terminate-then-immediate-quiescence).
+The state read is best-effort (D5): if it raises, the iteration skips the
+terminal check rather than crashing.
+
+**Terminal is once-per-deployment, restart-deduped.** The once-only flag
+is in-memory, so an orchestrator restart against an
+already-`terminated` experiment would re-fire. Before writing a terminal
+archive the scheduler checks whether a `<experiment_id>-terminated-*.tar`
+already exists in the destination and skips if so — so a restart does not
+produce a second terminal checkpoint.
+
+**Known gap:** if the orchestrator has already exited (quiescence) before
+an admin later terminates, no terminal checkpoint fires — the most recent
+periodic checkpoint is the safety net. A server-side on-terminate hook
+would close this but needs the task-store-server to own a destination +
+repo bundle + admin context; deferred to a follow-up (§4.2).
